# Git workflow

## Commits

- Conventional Commits: semantic subject + audit-useful rationale in the body.
- One logical change per commit: touch only the files required for that change;
  commit independent concerns separately.
- Outside plan mode, auto-commit completed work without asking — commits flow
  automatically in implementation mode. Pause and return to plan mode only if a
  fundamental design issue surfaces, or when the user pushes back on a recent change.
- Commit/PR audit trailers (Authored-By, Model, Session-ID, …) → my-audit-trail.

## Push / pull

- Push immediately after every commit, same turn — don't wait to be asked.
- Pull-rebase-before-push: always `git pull --rebase` before `git push`; on a
  non-fast-forward rejection, retry once with `git pull --rebase && git push`.
- Auto-proceed on read-only ops (status, diff, log, show, branch, pull, push,
  push --force-with-lease) without asking.

## Destructive ops — pause first

Pause before push --force, push --delete, rebase, reset, stash pop/drop, tag
unless the user explicitly requested that exact action in the current message.

## Stashes

Always `git stash push -m "<unique-slug>"` — never bare `git stash`. Pop by name.
Multiple agents share the stash stack; unnamed stashes collide.

## Multi-instance worktrees (mandatory before any file edit)

Concurrent agents on one branch race (last write wins); Write/Edit/Bash are
hook-blocked on the main checkout until inside a worktree.

1. `git pull`, then check claims: `todo.sh list @worktree`.
2. Create a worktree and work inside it.
3. Record the claim in todo.txt and commit it in the worktree's first commit.
   ← todo.txt format: my-task-tracking.
4. On completion, inside the worktree: mark the task done and commit. Then merge
   back by origin type:
   - GitHub origin (github.com or an Enterprise/self-hosted GitHub host, e.g.
     anything `gh` recognizes): push the branch and open a PR (`gh pr create`).
     When the PR is ready, self-review it per `my-code-review` before merging.
     Auto-merge (squash) ONLY if the repo owner is one of my own accounts
     ({{ .my.github_personal_owners | join ", " }}) — `gh pr merge --squash --delete-branch`. Any other
     owner (work/shared) → leave the PR open for review; do NOT auto-merge.
   - Non-GitHub / no remote, my own project (I work directly off main): squash-merge
     the branch into main — `git merge --squash <branch>` + single conventional
     commit — `git branch -D <branch>` (squash leaves it "unmerged", so `-d` fails),
     push.
   - Any other case (e.g. a non-GitHub remote that isn't mine): default to STOP —
     ask me how to proceed, and propose a concrete update to this skill so the
     new use-case is covered next time (see `my-agent-memory`).

### Worktree merge-back — what's agent-gated

The worktree guard blocks mutating git only on the **main checkout**, not in a
linked worktree:

- `git rebase main` to linearize the branch when main advanced runs **inside the
  worktree** (cwd = the worktree) — this is a worktree-local mutation, so it is
  **agent-allowed** and is NOT the gated step. Do it before integrating so the
  branch fast-forwards cleanly.
- Integrating into main is the gated boundary: a local `git merge` /
  `git merge --ff-only` into the main checkout is **blocked** (a human, or a
  `worktree-exempt` file, is required), whereas `gh pr merge` completes
  server-side and never touches the local main checkout, so it is
  **agent-allowed**. Prefer the PR path where available; otherwise hand the final
  local merge to the human.

